<br>
Same concept as in Quake, or any other FPS for that matter. The worst thing you could possibly do is team up on someone. You've significally shrunk your possible targets for gaining points, but doubled, tripled, even quaded "their's" depending on how badly you outnumber them."<br>
<br>
Your anology is flawed. In Quake, 1 kill = 1 "point." In EQ there are a lot of factors determining what 1 kill equals.<br>
<br>
The fact that evils have so little points has very little to do with them being the biggest or them having level 60's killing newbies (it makes some impact, but little... check the top negative scores).<br>
<br>
The simple fact of the matter is evils don't PvP in their lower or mid levels unless actually forced to. If they wanted to PvP, they would go look for it... go to everfrost, you can find plenty of goods to kill; go to velious (like anywhere, GD/EW/etc.) and you can find newts to kill (spinfusor and other iggles are the only ones I know who do this). Likewise overthere is the place to find evils 30 - 50 (there is usually several goods or neutrals in their PK'ing).<br>
<br>
So imo the whole size of the team is not a reason at all, that's stupid. Say that the server peaks at seven or eight hundred people... that's still a decent chunk of good and neutrals for evils to target - and because of the 1 character rule, the average level of people keep raising at a fast rate.<br>
<br>
The argument of level 60's ganking level 60's is null also - both teams have these people... don't make it out like only evils do this.<br>
